My girls are 11 and have been taking these antioxidants for years. Their only vet visits to this very day have been their annual checkups and little chiro adjustments as a precaution, to keep them aligned (they're part Dachsund) -- that's it -- NO health issues to speak of, EVER, knock on wood! Is their great health due only to this supplement? Likely not. However, I do trust that it contributes to their healthy immune systems.

reviewText: This product is a lot of help...I rescue animals and so I keep this product on hand.  It is kitten formula but I use it for undernourished or sick cats as well. I recently moved from California to Ohio and driving my cat wasn't an option, as he is 13 years old and gets very, very car sick almost immediately. He'd never been on a plane before, let alone outside of the house except for annual vet visits. So my wife and I decided that I'd fly the cat to a very nice pet hotel near the Columbus airport and then fly back home and we'd drive with our 13-year-old dog -- which is too large to fly in-cabin (and we didn't want to risk losing her in cargo).

Our cat is like our kid (especially to my wife) so we had to make sure to get the right carrier. We shopped and compared several airline-approved carriers and decided on the Sherpa based on reviews. Since you can only take one carry-on bag and one personal item, we appreciated the zipped pockets and storage areas of the Sherpa. We put in wetnaps, cat toys, food and snacks and a water dispenser (I filled once I got past security).

You need to take the cat out when going through security, so I asked to do that in the private room you'd otherwise never want to see. The TSA were very nice and understanding. And the process went without the cat escaping into the airport.

There were a couple of times when our cat was obviously unhappy during the flight, but overall he did fantastic. He slept mostly and had plenty of room in the Sherpa. We put an absorbent pad under the included fleece liner but fortunately the cat was able to hold it until he got outside and into his cat suite at the pet hotel.

Two thumbs up (and two paws) from my cat and I for the Sherpa.
summary: PERFECT for taking your cat on an airplane

I have three cats, one with urinary issues. I have him on the prescription Hill's dry food, and it's expensive, but it's worth it to keep him healthy. For wet food, I've stayed with Friskies--it's cheaper, and he'll eat it, which is important. I tried the Purina ProPlan Urinary formula, and the one with urinary issues wouldn't touch it. I was a bit skeptical of this food, but all three of my cats absolutely LOVE it! It's still pricey--as of this review, 24 2.9 oz cans are just over $20--so I won't be using this as the main wet food, but it makes for a great snack.

The big question--does it work? Well, that's hard to know--as I said, I'm not using this as the main food for my cats, just a supplement. I haven't seen any reduction in hair balls yet, but I also haven't seen a resurgence of urinary issues. So I'm happy with it, but I also won't be replacing any of my cats' other food with it in the future.

Unfortunately with issues like canine epilepsy, diet can be critical, so I feed her only grain- and preservative-free kibble. But these pill pockets, though handy (and apparently tasty) are made with wheat and corn syrup, two ingredients I (like other owners of special-needs dogs) go out of our way to avoid.

I like the assurance of being able to wrap her meds in the squishy treat. But I do wish these squishy, tasty treats didn't contain the very ingredients we're trying to avoid. Hence the three-star rating for what should really be a five-star product.
summary: Helps make sure the pill gets where it's supposed to.

I have bought around 15 different glucosamine products from Amazon for my three large golden retrievers. I have worried about their hips since they have a tendency of having problems with joints, especially hip dysplasia. I have had multiple goldens with these ailments and I am trying out make sure my current goldens do not have the same problems. I have tried the powder, liquid, and pill version, but our dogs are not a big fan of most of them. We go through so much glucosamine for our dogs since I have three around 100 pounds. It seems like anything I buy does not last very long and I feel like I buy a new bottle of glucosamine for my dogs almost every week. This can be really pricey, but I know that they need it with all of the hip and joint problems.

With this Gillick K9 glucosamine, I give each dog around 2 tablespoons (1 ounce) each day and there are 32 fl. ounces (1 quart) of glucosamine in the bottle. My dogs can always tell which Amazon box has the treats in it and they were eager for me to open the package. Even though I couldn't smell it, they could smell it through the bottle and were very excited to try it. When I opened it, (it took a long time to get the seals off) my dogs were really excited for it. It does not have a very strong scent and it is a thick yellow color. This bottle does not come with a pump or a pour out cap. You have to unscrew the lid and guesstimate 2 tablespoons. When you pour it, it runs down the mouth of the bottle and has to be wiped. I wish it had a pour cap or pump because it would be a cleaner way to use it. When you are done with this, you just have to throw it in the refrigerator to store.

I am happy with this product especially since it is made in the USA and has glucosamine, msm, and chondroitin which help to promote healthy joints and movement. The other ingredients include: 100% pure alove vera juice, purified water, natural flavoring, citric acid, stevia, potassium benzoate, potassium sorbate and shellfish. This does not contain any surgar, starch, salt, wheat, gluten, yeast, milk, or soy derivatives. I would ideally like a product that didn't contain stevia, but my dogs love it regardless. On the back of the bottle it says that the statments haven't been evaluated by the FDA. The product is manufactured in a GMP facility. The bottle is BPA free and it is made in the USA! My dogs are able to maintain a healthy and active lifestyle without joint pain thanks to glucosamine!

 I hope that this review has been helpful to you!!!
summary: Made in the USA, doesn't smell, 1 quart, my dogs love it!

I have used this product on two cats.  It was great for one of them and not so good for the other.  I'll describe both their experiences and hopefully that will help you decide whether this product might be right for your own cat.

Monkey: He is a lovely long-haired kitty with a tendency to get soft stools.  I notice, because it gets stuck in his fur.  There's not always an obvious cause for his problem -- he's resistant to eating anything other than his own food, and he never goes outside.  But about a week of FortiFlora clears the problem right up, each and every time.  There's been a time or two he's been on antibiotics, and FortiFlora has helped keep his stools firm then, too.  He loves the taste and gets very excited whenever I get out one of the little packets.  So it's been great for him.

Mouse: She was a sweet little short-haired gray tabby with a bad case of inflammatory bowel disease.  We used this product for awhile, but it did not help.  In fact, it may have made the problem worse.  FortiFlora contains something called "animal digest" that is designed to enhance palatability (and seems to, in Monkey's case), but which is likely to contain some animal proteins that aggravate IBD symptoms.  (If you are not familiar with feline IBD, many common proteins may trigger symptoms -- including, in some cases, chicken, pork, beef, turkey, etc. in addition to grains.)

In conclusion, if you have an otherwise healthy cat on a course of antibiotics or with occasional soft stools, you should definitely try FortiFlora.  But if you have a cat with a food allergy or with IBD, you should probably not use it.  Also, don't open the packets around your own food (the powder is light and can puff up a bit when you pour it out) and wash your hands after dispensing -- the bacterial strain is an Enterococcus one that you don't necessarily want in your own system.
summary: worth a try, but not suitable for every cat

It's hard to write a review of the results - because they could be right, and they could be wrong!  I have no way to know.  And, I will say that you cannot always judge a dog's heritage by its appearance ... I have met people with mixed-breed dogs where I was SURE that the dog was, for example, a lab/pit mix, and the owner will say "no, I saw both parents, it's a border collie / doberman mix."  Or two breeds I absolutely could not see in the dog.  So, keep that in mind when you get unexpected results!

My own dog Cassidy is long haired, red and white, and she blows her undercoat like a Samoyed or Husky.  I have always thought she was an Australian Shepherd / Siberian Husky mix.  Her DNA came back as:

25% Golden Retriever, 25% Akita, 25% Giant Schnauzer, and then one of her grandparents was a mixed breed dog, with the five breeds with the strongest statistical probability being, in descending order: Border Collie, Portuguese Water Dog, Basenji, Bearded Collie, and Samoyed.

I can see the Golden, especially in her plumage.  Other people can see the Akita (I cannot), and there's no trace of Giant Schnauzer in her appearance.  She could definitely be part Border Collie rather than Australian Shepherd though.  And she blows her coat like a Samoyed!

So ... the one thing that gives me pause, however, is the idea that three of her grandparents were purebreds and very expensive ones at that, and somehow they managed to mate outside their breed?  I mean, I know that if she's 25% Akita, it's possible that she had two grandparents who were each half-Akita, but that's a pretty rare breed, so it's more likely that one grandparent was a purebred Akita.  And - I can't see an Akita owner just letting his dog mate with some random Golden Retriever, Giant Schnauzer or mixed breed dog!

Anyway, in terms of customer service, I was pleased that the kit includes a postage paid priority mail envelope.  I got the results about two weeks after sending in the swabs, and the on-line PDF (which you can download and/or print) was very nicely formatted.  I somehow lost the email and then it turns out I never created an account, so I called the 800 number and the customer service rep looked up my name, and gave me my sample number, and two years after buying the test, I was able to enter that data and download the PDF to my computer, something I should have done at the time. I could also give that information to my friends and they could look up my dog's results if they wanted to.  So - this is a mix of commerce and science, I believe, and is only as good as (a) the size of the data bank they have and (b) the number of alleles they test.  And obviously the more they test, the more costly it is for them and the less money they make.  So it's a balancing act for Mars Veterinary - to provide good results while still making a profit.

Anyway here's a picture of my Cassidy - tell me what you think?!
summary: Fun, maybe accurate, quick turnaround, glad I did it.

This box has worked out well for us. We have two of them and I'm about to order two more. We were previously using Scoop Free with the Forever Litter tray, a fantastic system that had kept us happy for over 10 years. But one of our new kittens simply would not adjust to the crystals. We had to switch to clay (when she was old enough). Fortunately all of the cats are happy with the clay. Even better, I'm actually happier with the clay than I had been with the crystals. We're using the Petco "So Phresh" clumping clay litter which comes in a bucket you can refill at the store. All 5 of our cats prefer this litter over the crystals so we've had to switch to it in all of the boxes. The only problem we were facing was litter getting sprayed all over the place. When I saw the shape of the corners of these boxes, I was concerned about scooping and thought it might be difficult with the curves. However it has been no problem at all. We've been using the boxes for almost a month now. There is minimal tracking out the front, easily mitigated by the little rug we have in front of the boxes. The Petco litter has really surprised me by being such high quality. There is no smell whatsoever. I had switched to crystals because of their superior odor control, but the Petco litter is doing an incredibly good job. No smell. And the clumps are quite solid. It's very easy to scoop them out even when they are up against a curved corner in this box. We do scoop every day. We keep the litter about 3 to 4 inches deep. We use a Litter Genie which is a product I only wish I'd discovered earlier. We have one gigantic long haired cat, and I thought this box might be too small for him, but he seems to be perfectly fine with it. We have one much larger box in another location closer to where he spends most of his time, but he still goes downstairs to use these boxes quite often. In case you are concerned to hear about clumping clay litter and kittens, don't worry, we didn't try the clay until they were quite old enough for it to not be a problem. (Clumping clay litter can be bad for little kittens as they can ingest it when cleaning themselves and it can block their digestive system.)
summary: Great litter box. Keeps the litter from being kicked out all over the place. Easy to scoop. Even our giant cat likes it.

reviewText: I am a bit skeptical about things like this working but this totally worked for my cat!  First let me start by telling you that my cat is a total scardy cat. She runs and hides the minute a stranger enters, but she patrols my house like a watchdog!!! Well, some wild animal was coming onto my deck at night and terrorizing her through the sliding glass doors. Fights so vicious and aggressive that I thought something had gotten in my house ... my cat ran and hide under my bed and howled and hissed for over an hour after that fight ... The next morning she seemed okay... I picked her up and petted her but when I put her on the ground she turned and hissed at me and ran away and hide ... this is very unusual behavior and I knew I had to do something.  I remembered reading about this and thought it couldn't hurt right??? So I put a few drops on her food morning and night to make sure she was getting it ... the wild animal returned a few days later ... hissing ensued but my cat retreated and was not traumatized ... each time the beast returned the fights got shorter and shorter until the beast stop coming or my cat stopped engaging .... I credit the rescue remedy in helping her gain confidence and remain calm after these encounters.  Thank god the beast has moved on and life is back to normal but I now have RR on hand just in case!!!
summary: Helped my cat get over traumatic wild beast encounter!

reviewText: Dogs are allergic to avocados - it can be a stomach irritant.  I am tired of dog food companies who claim to love dogs and want to make them healthy treats including ingredients that are great for humans --  but not for dogs.  Garlic Powder is another offender I often see, which ruptures red blood cells in dogs and cats and can cause anemia, if given in small amounts over a period of time.  Many dogs are also reactive to chicken and get skin bumps (mine does.)  I am happy to see so many companies using better ingredients in general, but BEWARE of allergens.

I purchased this harness after my dog got in an altercation with another dog at day care. He suddenly became fear reactive toward large dogs after said altercation, and I didn't feel safe taking him outside in his Freedom harness anymore. I felt like if he really wanted to, he could escape from the Freedom harness - it's slung low in the front and if tightened too much rubs his hair off.

Enter the Ruffwear Front Range. I like that this has the front clip if we need it (which we sometimes use right now - it's Autumn which means the squirrels are in high gear and have complete disregard for my dog, who would love to 'play' with them) and I also love how high it sits on his neck. It is a little bit difficult to get on and off, but my dog doesn't mind. I also like how it stays away from areas of high motion, such as his armpits, shoulders
and chest. It seems walking in this is more comfortable for him, as his previous harness impeded his gait slightly. Another thing that I love is the ID tag pocket - I like that I don't have to have my dog wear his collar, as he does not wear one when we are in the house. I didn't love how he had to wear one with his old harness.

I chose this harness above the Web Master as I needed something where he could not escape out the front - he has never been able to back out of a harness. I was skeptical that the Medium would fit him - he is a bigger dog so typically he wears large, but this fits him well. My only concern is that the back portion of this harness might sit up too high, but it's minor (half an inch, maybe) and does not affect the fit and purpose otherwise.

We are now working hard to get my pup back to his old self, and thanks to the Ruffwear Front Range Harness, it's a little bit easier. I no longer fear the reliability of the equipment I am using, which allows me to focus on rehabilitating my dog. Thanks, Ruffwear!
summary: Helping me to help my dog!

I love the idea of this system. Unfortunately, my cat doesn't seem to like it as yet. I haven't given up as yet. I think he didn't like the feel of those pellets as he is declawed. I wish I hadn't done that to him, but we got him at a time when we had another cat that was declawed and didn't want the new guy to have an unfair advantage. So I have read MANY of the reviews. I have thought about the various changes to the pellets, and decided that something smooth and easy on the paws was what I should try next. I have removed the pellets, and put sifted pea gravel in place of the pellets. Sifted because there is some material that is sand and tiny size that must be removed. My rational is I will probably scoop the poops (if he will ever use it) very soon after he goes anyway. I have been in the habit of cleaning his litter box out daily anyway. In this process I have let his old box go unscooped for several days at a time- till I couldn't stand it anymore (YUCK). After the pea gravel change he was at least interested enough to go smell and look at it. I think he might have #1 in it, as there is a stain on the pad underneath. But then I couldn't tolerate the AWFUL unscooped poopy box and cleaned it out. This probably set me back again! Now I am letting the pile build up again in hopes he will go back to the nice new pea gravel box. I am hesitant to totally remove his old box as I don't want an accident. My son who bought the same system did that as his cats wouldn't try this new box either. His cats "figured it out" when he took away the old box. Just kind of leery of doing that.

Although my cats ate it and seemed to like it, the problems started about 12-24 hrs later. Severe and sudden diarrhea (meaning they often didn't have time to make it to the litter box), upchucking, really not a fun time for any of us. It got so bad I called the vet (I'd already taken the food away) to see if I needed to bring them in. Her advice was to remove this food, switch back to the Fromm and see if things cleared up. I'm happy to say they are doing better (It's been about 24 hrs since I replaced the food). Obviously, this is an exception, and it seems from the other reviews that most cats would probably do just fine on this. I'm still not sure precisely what ingredient(s) set them off, but something in this food seemed to cause a lot of "digestive distress" with my two Devon Rex kitties. We won't be trying this brand again. Sorry.

It's not the healthiest dog treat. The first ingredient is wheat and the third ingredient is sugar. For everyday use, we choose to use other treats that are primarily made from meat and vegetables, and that don't have added sugar and other nutritionally poor ingredients. However, my dog loves these, so we occasionally give her one or two.

Unlike many other treats, these are not easy to break into small pieces, so they are not great for trick training. They are too big to give a dog many at one time. For trick training, we use treats that can easily be broken into small pieces, so that we can offer many rewards without ending up over feeding.

My favorite thing about these treats is that they throw really well. Frankly, their effective function as delicious projectiles is the primary reason we buy these. I always try to carry some on walks so that if an off-leash dog tries to interact with our fearful dog, we can throw some to the unattended dog to get them to leave our dog alone. Works great. Having a dog who is fearful and/or aggressive on leash can be stressful, so it's important to find as many strategies as possible to resolve the potential problems that come up while out and about. Not all dogs who come running at ours respond to food, but many have, and these throw really well and are not too pricy.
summary: Junk Food Ingredients, But Throws REALLY, REALLY Far

reviewText:
We have many Kyjen toys and they are wonderful!  Their customer service is fabulous too.  This Dinosaur is somewhat different from his Egg Babies Playpus in that the size of the opening for the eggs is different.  It is slightly elasticized and a snug fit for the eggs to fit out.  In our case our Mini Aussie Shepard LOVED the snugger fit.  It kept him going after those eggs for half an hour before we intervened.  The Dino was fine but soaked in slobber:>)  The Platypus opening is a bit larger and the elastic less noticeable so it was much easier to remove the eggs through.  If your dog hasn't played with these before consider getting the Platypus to start then move on to the Dino if your dog becomes as addicted to them as ours has.  Yep, he fixates on these and we wouldn't trade them for anything.

They wear very well and wash up great.  He plays endlessly with the eggs once they are out but hasn't turned them into chew toys.  I purchased a spare Platypus just in case his favorite toy falls apart one day but the original is still going strong after 4 months.  We bought the Dino thinking the bright colors would be easy to spot in the garden and we weren't wrong.  We don't want him digging beside us so throwing the dino in the washer each day it's outside is a small price to pay!
summary: Dinosaur is Awesome for Dogs Already Familiar With Egg Babies!

I absolutely LOVE this product. Before finding the Kool Collar, my dog couldn't run in the heat at all.  I had to wait for dark to run her. Now we can go while it is still daylight. It doesn't completely keep her cool due to the rapid melting of the ice/warming up of the insert, but it gives her at least 20 minutes of not overheating.  I have started bringing along a second insert, carrying it in a little cooler on my bike so that I can change them halfway.  That gives us extra walk time.  Well, run time, LOL... she likes to go!

I prefer the insert to the ice.  The ice is very bulky and my dog didn't seem to like it.  Using it with the insert, she enthusiastically sticks her head through it when I hold it out. Happy dog! Oh, also, the collar is very lightweight, unlike some of those "bandanas" that are offered for dogs.

UPDATE: The little ice inserts didn't last long - they leaked and became flat and useless.  So I ended up using real ice, which worked once I figured out the right amount to use so that it wasn't too tight yet would have enough ice to last for at least 20-30 minutes.  Now I prefer the ice as it did get her neck good and wet, promoting evaporation and thus, cooling.  Here in Florida this product is invaluable.  When I am planning on a longer run I bring some extra ice in a small fabric cooler, which works very well.

I previously rated this product very high (5 stars).. GREAT ingredients, and my cat loved it.. She enjoyed it for many many months.

In December I ordered a large 'supply' for the home. We broke into this new batch and suddenly my cat started to get very sick.. Vomiting, foaming at the mouth, lethargic. We didn't tie it to the food, since we've always fed her this. Then she REFUSED to eat it, she would start to eat it, then stop, and walk away. We knew the cat wasn't sick because she would eat canned tuna, and another brand of food I purchased. I put her BACK ON this, and she became sick immediately.

Then I read the reviews here, and found another reviewer got the tainted batch, and it was making her cat very sick as well!  Suddenly it all started to make sense.. I am never trusting this brand again after this.. I picked up Blue Buffalo today, and my cat is viciously eating it, like she hasn't had a good meal for weeks! I could tell me cat was 'worried' it was the crappy food, she sniffed, looked it over, then started to go nuts on the Blue Buffalo.

Sheba shipped a tainted batch, and I wonder if ingredients are sourced in China? China sourced food products are dangerous, and I read a lot of cat food companies are starting to source primarily in China.. Be careful!

I'm a life-long dog owner and aware of the dangers of poor dental care. However in spite of proper feeding/care our 6 year old Beagle developed bad tarter on his back teeth and our vet advised cleaning as soon as possible. Not wanting to subject him to anesthesia I started researching plaque removal products. After reading other reviews I purchased this product at a local pet store. It's AMAZING. Using twice a day for less than a month he has nearly puppy-white teeth. I did brush the back teeth a couple of times to loosen the plaque with seemed helpful.  Once I saw the product was working I started using it on my son's Puggle too with excellent results. The 2.2 ounce bottle lasted 6 weeks, spraying the Beagle twice daily for the first month and once every couple of days after that. I am so impressed I ordered an 8 oz refill for myself (for less than I paid for the original small bottle) and two other bottles for my daughter's and sister's dogs. I can't wait to take my dog back to the vet and tell/show him how effective this product is. Although this is an all natural product I did notice some redness of the gums when I was doing the twice daily treatment. The alcohol might be a little harsh but it doesn't last long and tooth decay is worse. I highly recommend this product.

I have a ten year old Bichon Frise who has always been unintimidated by severe weather.  She has unflinchingly gone out in all sorts of weather, including hurricanes and we have never had a problem.

Earlier this year, however, we adopted a rescue dog with a real fear of water.  Just looking out the door or window on a rainy day makes her miserable.  When we take her outdoors in the rain, she acts as if she thinks she is made of candy floss and will melt if she gets wet.  She is a long haired Maltese mix and looks absolutely miserable with the long strands of wet hair hanging in her face.  Although we put a raincoat on her, she cant see well with a hood on so she shakes it off and then suffers the consequences.  Holding an umbrella over her has always been a tricky prospect, especially if I have both dogs out.  At times, I have had the water pour off the edge of my umbrella right into her face :(

When we got the Lesypet umbrella, it was during a sunny rain free week.  I tried the umbrella leash on her while indoors and, except for an initial bit of confusion about what I was trying to accomplish, she had no problem walking under it.  When the rain came back this week, I was so eager to try it and it more than met my expectations.  This umbrella is just ingenious.  Its transparent so she can clearly see me and the world around her while staying dry.  The cane shaped umbrella handle is easy to hold even while holding another dogs leash.

We highly recommend this solution for any other dogs who absolutely hate rain coming down on their faces.

Disclosure: A complimentary product was sent to me for trial and evaluation. I have no connection to the seller or the manufacturer and my review is based solely on my perception of the merits of the product.
summary: Makes going out on rainy days easier for my cotton candy floss dog

I have a Rottweiler puppy, now six months old.  I had had her on a different food for the first couple of months after I brought her home, and while that food (Innova Large Breed Puppy) resulted in appropriate growth rate and energy level, she ALWAYS had mushy stools.  It didn't matter whether I fed her small amounts at a time, whether I added pumpkin, whether I added yogurt, or anything else.

After giving the other food a chance for a couple of months, I decided to try something else (after confirming, of course, that my puppy did not have a bacterial infection or any intestinal parasites).  I had a list of brands in mind; Wellness was one of them.  Since it was the only food from my list available in a large bag from the store where I was, at the time, that's what I bought.  I made the switch slowly, over the period of about 10 days.

About a week after my puppy was on the Wellness exclusively, I noticed her stools had started firming up.  (That may be a little gross to talk about, but it is something I was quite concerned about since I have to pick up after her!)  After a month or so, they're now completely normal (my baseline being the last dog I had).  My puppy also has an appropriate amount of energy on this food, can handle a lot of it (she's still growing!), has a beautiful shiny coat and bright eyes, and is gaining weight at an appropriate rate.  She likes the taste and empties the bowl in a short period of time.

The food comes in a resealable bag for freshness.  It is one of the more expensive dry puppy foods on the market, but I think it's keeping my dog in such good shape that I'm saving on vet costs.  I'm also comforted by Wellness's reputation for using high-quality ingredients without a lot of filler.

I just received this item today.  I took it out of the box and took it apart to see what I am working with.  So here are my thoughts on the actual product.  Yes, as other viewers has stated, it is made of foam.  It is high density foam, not the kind coolers or plates are made of.  The material makes it light enough to not be difficult to handle, it feels sturdy and is firm but comfortable at the same time.  I unzipped the cover and checked it out.  I like that it can be cleaned easily.  The pillow/cushion in the seat is a lot thicker than I thought it would be and it seems like it will be very comfortable for my dogs.  I got the large seat and have a 10 lb poodle, and a 10 lb chiwennee and they both fit in the seat and would be able to move around and lay down comfortably.  The only thing I can see I would improve on is I wish the leash went into the foam instead of just being sewn into the cover.  Seems it would be safer.  But it is still safer than my tiny dog laying on my leather seats when some jack hole pulls out in front of me and I have to slam my breaks and send him flying into the floor board (which happened recently).  Luckily I caught him before he could hit the floor.  So I am glad I made the investment and I think I chose the right product.  I will update when my dog has actually had a chance to ride in it.  He has a vet appointment on Saturday and I will know then.

Update:  I finally got the chance to use my booster seat and I love it.  My boy dog Jax loved being able to either lie down and sleep (like he always does when riding) or stand and look out the windows (which he never gets the chance to do)  I put blankets in it  because it is cool out here in Coastal GA and the smell of familiar items kept them comfortable.  My girl dog was not crazy about it, but she hates to ride.  That is not a reflection of the seat, but her own stubbornness.  I got the large and it was plenty of room for both of them to sit or lay.  They are 9 & 8 lbs. and fit perfectly.  The seat was easy to install in the center of my back seat.  I had to tweak the seat belt a little because I drive a Volvo and all of the seat belts have shoulder straps and it wanted to lift the right side of the seat.  After putting the seat belt together with a zip tie, it sat flat down.  I love having this product and am glad I invested in it because it keeps my babies from flying all over the car when making turns or putting ion the breaks.  Having them ride comfortably and safely keeps me more focused on driving and less focused on their safety or worrying about where in the car they are.

Unfortunately I just bought the new bag and I didn't want to waist it or return it so my dog finished the bag. I know better next time. reviewText: We found Glyco-Flex III Soft-Chews for Dogs, 120-Count and DVM Resources SynoviG3 Soft Chews, 240 Chews to be effective for arthritic dogs, but "Triple Joint Max" to be a waste of money. I have to wonder if it actually contains what it claims to contain on the label. I don't see how there could be such a significant difference in the effect is there is similar amounts of the same ingredients (compared to the other joint chews mentioned). After just one week on the Synovi G3, there is a visible improvement from what was seen on "Triple Joint Max". If you do find your dog has some relief from this product, please try the others as well. You may, as we did, see a significant improvement in how your dog feels and behaves. I am dedicated to research and cross checking what I think/feel to be the truth. I have never been more sure that a product is not worth it's price. For 10% more money, you can receive a lot more relief for your pet. Don't you owe them that? In the months that we experiments with the more affordable joint chew, we saw serious degeneration. Because we had a donation of several packages, we tried the "1-800-pet meds" brand joint ches in higher than recommended doses for 4 months (her decline seemed fairly steady for about 3 months then remained about the same). I then tried "Triple Joint Max" for about 5 weeks. During that time she did not improve. In just 3 months, the dog we were treating with the "cheap" products deteriorated rapidly. It was so bad, she was screaming in pain at night. This dog went from being able to walk 5 miles with no issues, to only being able to walk 1/2 mile slowly. A switch back to the Synovi G3 showed significant improvement in just a week. At this rate, I would expect her to rebuild her muscle and be able to handle 4 mile walks within a month. Even though I know Synovi G3 works, I am open to seeing if there is indeed something that may be better. For this dog, I am going to switch to the Dasuquin chews for a few weeks and see what happens. I will report back. UPDATE: The Dasuquin chewsDasuquin Soft Chews for Dogs 60 lbs and over, 84 Chews are wonderful!! I give them 5 stars! The dog has improved drastically in only 1 1/2 weeks. Today we walked over a mile at a fast speed and she showed no desire to stop and rest. She even wanted to play in the park at the end of the walk. Joint Chews I've used, listed in order of effectiveness: 1) Dasuquin Chews (By far the Best) 2) Synovi G3 (pretty darn great) 3) Glycoflex 3 (pretty darn good) 4) Triple Joint Max (Not very effective) 5) 1800 pet meds super joint chewies (not effective from what I can tell) Good Luck to all the dog lovers out there! PS A raw, carb-free diet is great for arthritic dogs.

This de-shedder works so much better than those wire slicker brushes I've always used for my cats. I've got a short-hair and a long-hair. This works great for both. It doesn't damage their coats at all.

Short-Hair Cat:
The slicker brushes and the rubber ones never got much from my short-haired cat leaving hands, clothes, and furniture covered in little orange hairs. This de-shedding tool gets enough off of him that it has dramatically decreased how much loose hair ends up everywhere from him. He also hated being groomed by every other brush or tool I've tried, but this this barely bothered him at all - he was apprehensive at first, as he often is of new things, but once he sniffed it and inspected it he let me groom him just fine.

Long-Hair Cat:
The wire slicker brushes had decent luck with my long-haired cat, but they always caused his fur to become static-y. I'd groom him and he'd look worse than he did before I brushed him. This tool left his coat much softer than a slicker brush ever has, and got more hair from him. While not totally static-free, there was far less of it with this comb. It also seems to irritate his skin much less than other grooming tools have, as his dandruff has improved with the use of this comb. Also, he loved being groomed with this. Purring and sleepy-eyed the whole time.

Why 4 Stars?
I docked this comb by one star because it gets the hair everywhere as it's combing it out. The comb doesn't trap the hair very well, beyond a small amount, which you have to pull from the tines by hand and pile up, where it will hopefully not drift off or get everywhere before you're done grooming. There was so much more hair flying around when I combed my cats with this tool than there is with a brush... but again, it also worked better at actually de-shedding.

Overall:
Absolutely a good investment, especially at the ~$15 it was when I bought it considering other similar tools can run $30+.
summary: Great tool, a little hairy during the grooming process though

I got this cover for the back seat of my car, to protect it from my cat, Buddy. I stay with my mom (she's 91 & suffers from Alzheimer's) in Seattle, half of the week and I've been doing this for over 3 years now. As anyone that acts as a caregiver (unpaid) to a family member knows, it is a stressful, emotionally draining, physically exhausting and downright dirty job. It's made even more difficult when the person becomes incontinent and it's not something I'd ever thought I'd sign up for. Ever since my dad died, 'us kids' took it upon ourselves to start caring for her and since Day 1, I've been taking my cat Buddy with me on my 'days on'. I really don't know how I could ever do it without him. He is truly my BFF and constant companion. I feel so blessed that he likes riding in the car with me. It's so cute, having him sitting alongside of me, on the center console, looking around and out the windows. Still, he has accidents on occasions (very few) and I decided it's best to cover the seats. Especially after I had to take over my daughter's car payments, after she moved abroad. This car is an '05, but it's still a very nice car, and I want to take good care of it.
What I like most about this particular backseat cover, is the fabric on the top side, the side that your pet lays on. It is so soft and velvety to the touch. It really does feel (and look), like suede (what they call micro-suede) and Buddy really like laying on it. It comes with it's own nylon drawstring carrying bag, for when you want to store it away, but I'll probably use it for some of his other supplies. I also like that this cover looks so luxurious. I honestly think it looks too nice for me to put on the back seat of my car, especially when I have the litter box, sitting over top of it...lol! But that's just there for 'just in case' he has an accident. I actually had this cover laid out over top of my bed (when it first arrived), and Buddy took to it instantly & lay right on top of it. It's so soft and feels good against the skin. Another good thing about it, is there's no factory/chemical 'stink'/smell to it. On the reverse side, the material is obvious to the eye, to be waterproof. It's made out of Polyester and has those little rubberized nub/dots on it. The stitching is very nice and I like how the whole thing is quilt stitched to keep the fabrics sewn together. There are 2 corners with elastic straps across them and 2 without. Along the top side, there are 2 adjustable buckle straps to use to attach to the backseats' headrests. And in the middle of the cover, are 2 velcro sealed openings, for in you want to use your car's seat belt. I think this is perfect for any pet and if he/she has an accident, this cover is totally machine washable (hang it to dry). It can also be wiped clean with a rag and some pet spot cleaning spray. I received this for free, in exchange for my honest and unbiased review, but I think the asking price for this product is still quite reasonable. It's a wise purchase and definitely better to protect your investment (your vehicle), just in case your pet should have a messy accident.
summary: This is a great product for protecting your car from pet accidents.

I used this on my dog who has rancid breath because I have not been diligent in brushing his teeth. He did not mind the taste too much and I read the reviews on poor taste, but decided to get it anyway. The pads are small to use, but that is not the reason I'm giving this product a poor review. After wiping down his teeth, I noticed the pad was able to pick up some stuff from his dirty teeth, so I was hopeful about these wipes.

Minutes later, my dog started making these awful gagging sounds. I looked it up and it sounded something similar to a "reverse sneeze", which can be benign, but possible causes are due to mucus irritation or the attempt to remove a foreign substances. I was tempted try another one just to see if it was a coincidence, but I refuse to put him through that, again.

I decided to do more research on Polysorbate 20: /LABORATORY ANIMALS: Subchronic or Prechronic Exposure/ A bubble bath containing 6 percent Polysorbate 20 produced severe irritation when instilled into the vaginal vaults of three beagle dogs once daily, 5 days a week, for 3 weeks. Mucosal lesions were characterized by redness, blistering, mucosal sloughing, and, in one case, fibrous adhesions. Histologic examination revealed marked diffuse erosion of the vaginal mucosa with necrotic and fibrinous exudate on the mucosal surface and a marked infiltration of polymorphonuclear leukocytes in the submucosal tissue. A subsequent, similar test with the same bubble bath diluted to 0.5 percent in water produced no visible findings that were attributable to treatment. Gross pathologic and histopathologic observations revealed no differences from saline-treated controls. ([...])

Long story short, Polysorbate 20 is not gentle on dogs mucosal layers...
summary: I was actually looking for a way to contact seller to get this off the market...DO NOT PAY FOR SOMETHING THAT CAN HARM YOUR DOG

reviewText:
I bought these steps for my 40 lb. Australian Shepherd who was having back issues, so she could get on the bed easier.  While she didn't prefer to use them, I did enough training to know that she could use them just fine.  They are rated for a lot more than 40 lbs. and under her weight the steps appeared to be stable.  They were very easy to assemble; make sure you don't see light between the pieces to get the best result.  There is a tip in the instructions about using dish washing liquid to lubricate the pieces so they snap together better; that was very helpful.  You might also want a rubber mallet or hammer to help.

As many other mentioned, the steps do slant a bit.  My dog did not find this to be a problem, especially during training when there was a treat to be had!  I think the steps would be perfectly fine if they did not slant, but I don't see a problem with the slant either.  I would advise that the floor below the bottom step not be slippery.  I have hardwood that is very slippery.  My dog was much more comfortable using these when I put them on an area rug so that she didn't slip when hitting the floor.

Lastly, the sage green color is very attractive.  It's a subtle, almost elegant, color.

I seriously believe that they pulled this gravel out of a river or similar and bagged it up.  It was wet in the bag and more dirty than I could ever have expected.  It had to be rinsed, and rinsed and rinsed and then some. Took it outside for many rinses with a strainer and a garden hose. A total of 4 hours rinsing. Even after all that and I thought it was clean, my tank clouded up pretty bad. I have a canister filter, so it cleared the water up in less than an hour.  Then I just cleaned out the filter and the impeller. But it's still dirty in my tank even after a few more gravel vacuums.  Strange things have been vacuumed from the gravel. Slime with streaks of brown, and today what looks like a clear egg case, very sticky and about the size of a pea.  What that is, I don't know but it worries me.  I haven't added anything else new to the tank in 5 years. I don't have live plants. My 37 gallon  tank is long time established with angelfish and that is not an angelfish egg.

It's beautiful gravel.  Varies from shades of ivory to some browns and a lot of grays.  The pebble size is 3mm to 10mm.  They're smooth pebbles, so they're safe for bottom dwellers.  The gravel is inert.  Won't change your PH or GH or KH.

I can't recommend it, though.  Whatever is in that gravel, whether it's bacteria or some sort of aquatic organism, really scares me.  I'm planning on increasing my water changes to twice weekly.  I just hope my fish don't get sick.
summary: Is It Safe For Your Fish?

My cat gets one scoop (I think it's equivalent to 1 cup) of dry food per day.  One bag lasts me just over three months.  Therefore, just as I am running low on one bag of food, my new bag of food arrives in the mail.  My cat can sometimes be picky about his food, and he seems to like this particular cat food just fine.  (I am basing this on how much of it he eats every day.)  Just as an FYI, I do supplement my cat with wet canned food.  He receives a quarter-can of wet food in the morning.  I put out the scoopful of dry Purina when I give him his wet food, and he eats his dry food at his leisure throughout the day and night.  His weight has been consistent at 13 lbs. for nearly 1.5 years.  I have very happy with the quality of the Purina and the auto-refill service through Amazon, and see no reason to discontinue this food/service any time in the near future.

There are many thinning shears available at wildly different prices, so I was afraid to use these shears when the company offered to let me try them out.  As with any shears, they must be comfortable to hold and have a sharp edge to give a nice clean cut that will not give split ends.  Thinning shears have more issues, notably hair snagging in the teeth.  That can be painful and have an already on-guard dog panic.

When I first opened the package, I was impressed that the scissors look much nicer than the price would suggest.  They are similar to my other more expensive shears in weight and materials.  The stainless steel seems high quality and should make upkeep minor.  The ergonomics are also good, with my fingers (I have medium sized hands) resting nicely in the grooves.  The hairs are cut cleanly and there are almost no snags.  I don't know of any thinning shears that have a perfect record there, but these come pretty close.  The teeth are spaced similar to a standard set of human thinning shears.

I can't think of anything critical to say about these shears, particularly for the price.  I would even recommend them for cutting human hair, unless you use a longer length.  I will let you know if they don't last through many haircuts.

I used this litter for my guinea pig.  I put the litter bin in the corner of the cage and filled it with the litter.  In 2 hours time, I noticed my guinea pig was using it and I thought, "Wonderful! Now the cage bedding will last a few days longer!"  However, in a couple of days, I noticed each corner of the cage was being utilized for evacuation.  I normally clean the cage 1-2 times/week as there is only 1 guinea pig (Wilson) and was really hoping the litter box would allow me 1-2 times/every two weeks, of course with normal emptying of the litter box.  That is where the problem lies.  I went in 1 day later to empty the litter bin and noticed the pellets had become quite mushy; almost clay-like.  I gave the cage a thorough clean and bathed my little piggie and found his poor little paws were caked with the wet cement remnants of the pellets.  I had to soap and and soak his little claws and manually clean them out.  No wonder he stopped using the litter bin after 1 day.  I think it works to direct the guinea pig to evacuate in that spot, however, you will have to empty and replace everyday and that can get expensive...  I decided to finish the bag of litter and have chosen not to buy it again as the regular cage filler works fine in his litter bin and he prefers it as he has been using his litter bin 70% and the corners of his cage 30%.  If you are going to try this litter, you should change it at least once a day (depending on how much your little cavvy eats) because as soon as they empty their bladder, the pellets will turn to mush and it is not fun to clean that out.  Also, I have lined my piggies cage with fleece liners which he seems to like as he doesn't relieve himself on them.  Hope that helps!  :)
summary: May work initially, but you will have replace every 12 hours....

First off, this is not some magical solution that will transform your dog overnight. It is not an alternative to solid obedience and behavior training. That said, it has done wonders for both of my dogs. I was lucky that they both fell into the 80% of dogs that are helped by DAP. To give you an idea of how DAP can help, here are the stories of my two dogs: Hobbes is reactive and gets over excited easily. He used to bark at cars when we went on walks and would stare out the window all day barking at people walking past. We joined a class based on the book Control Unleashed: Creating a Focused and Confident Dog, which teaches dogs how to calm themselves. Despite great progress, he was still having some troubles, including lunging and growling at people when he was scared. Our instructor recommended we start using DAP in addition to a Thundershirt and calming music. The improvement over the first couple weeks was so gradual that it was hardly noticeable. Overall he was calmer and happier, no longer barking as much or lunging at cars on walks. However, after 4 weeks when the diffuser ran out there was a distinct and abrupt worsening. He was on edge again and more apt to bark. When our refills arrived, he quickly calmed down. Ivy had been an outgoing, playful dog until a month ago when she suddenly became scared of going outside after several days of skateboarders using our street to practice their moves. She hid all day long under the bed, and we had to carry her outside to go potty because she refused to go on her own. The vet started her on Prozac, and incidentally we started the DAP for Hobbes around the same time. After a month, she seemed to be getting better, more willing to come out and play. We weren't sure if this was due to the meds or the DAP. When the DAP ran out, she was suddenly back to hiding all day long and refusing to go outside. With the refill, she will now come out and play. She still has a long road to get back to her previous playful self, but it's an improvement. With both dogs, we used a variety of training techniques and other comfort measures: Thundershirt Dog Anxiety Treatment, Large, Heather Grey,Through a Dog's Ear: Music to Calm Your Canine Companion, Volume 1. Anyone who thinks that they can solve a dog's fear problem with one product without any training is going to be sorely disappointed. DAP can take the edge off of the fear so that training can be effective.
summary: Works well as adjunct to behavior training

reviewText:
EDIT:  This product has been changed.  I bought it again and the new trimmer is much smaller and barely cuts hair between my dogs toes at all.  Since my previous review was a glowing five stars, you know I would give credit if credit was due.  I was tempted to give it two stars, but "I hate it" really covers my thoughts on the new one I just tried out today and am sending back ASAP.

Prior review:
This product is a trimmer (translate that as 'shaver') for dog hair.  I have a Cavalier King Charles Spaniel, and hair grows on her paws between the pads.  The main benefit of this particular model is the T-shape; it allows you to get between the dogs toes and pads effectively. .  If you need something to groom your dog all over, this isn't it.  It isn't designed to groom your pet.  But if you want to clean out between the pads and toes, then this is just the ticket.

Read on if you don't mind my meandering style...

If my dog's underpaw fur is not trimmed (shaved) off, then she slip-slides around on the wood floors; when it gets too long, she doesn't want to jump down off furniture onto the floor by herself.  I had been using a rechargeable men's beard groomer for the 1st four years of her life, which worked OK because Cavaliers have very soft fur.  It was tricky to try to clean out thoroughly between the pads, though, because it was not designed to perform that maneuver.

Well, that rechargeable battery wouldn't charge anymore, so I bought this corded model.  Since I don't walk around while trimming the fur, cordless is pointless and less powerful anyway, so I wanted a corded model this time.  I considered a groomer model, because it sounded like a good idea to get something with more power plus attachments for just a few dollars more, but then I thought about it; I only need to do the paws and the T-shape looked like it would get between the paws and the toes BETTER than the groomer models would.  Not surprisingly (ha-ha!), I was right.  I paid about $2 less at a major Arkansas-based retail chain, but I would have gladly paid the extra two bucks for delivery if I hadn't been going there anyway.

I don't know how long it took for the product to get hot for the reviewers who said it did, but I did not have that problem at all.  Not the part I held and not the blade.  But Cavaliers are small, only 18 pounds, and have soft fur, so maybe if you had a really BIG dog or cat that could happen?  But frankly, that doesn't seem to be the problem the negative reviewers had; it seems like they were trying to groom their pets with a trimmer.  If you need to both groom your pet and ALSO to clean out between the pads and toes, I think I would look for a model with the T-shape on at least one blade or else buy a groomer AND buy this trimmer.

Finally, the noise of the trimmer is a buzzing just like an electric shaver.  It isn't jarring but it is not "whisper quiet" either.  My dog hates the vacuum cleaner, but this didn't bother her.
summary: Edited review: [NOT] Perfect for cleaning between pads and toes

The aggressive kitty had been attacking the sick kitty for about a month and a half I noticed. The vet suggested Feliway to put the aggressive kitty at ease since she said he probably has anxiety due to the situation and a built up frustration of no longer having a play mate to wrestle and play with.

Let me start by saying I work from home. Now to my dog...if I am home, that means that I am there to play with him and entertain him and walk him and love him. My boss, on the other hand, would prefer that I spend 8 hours a day working on deliverables for our clients. Until my dog and my boss can come to an agreement, I have to do what my boss wants since in the end, that is what keeps the kibble coming.

I have quite a few doggy-puzzles in this house so that I can work in peace. The Hide-a-Squirrel was great but eventually was destroyed. Bones are great as long as you can supervise. Kongs are probably the greatest invention for dogs on the face of the planet. I read about the Squirrel Buddy and Kibble Nibble when I was getting ready to buy a Tug-A-Jug.  I tend to give one puzzle at a time so the dog doesn't get bored. I haven't tried the other products yet, but for the Kibble Nibble:

1) My dog is on large breed Iams puppy. His kibble is average sized, not too large. The kibble came out at an acceptable, easy pace but to make it last longer and keep him occupied I chopped up some carrots and put those in as well. The larger carrots help slow down the flow of kibble. At the end, I just dump the carrots into his bowl and then wash the toy.

2) It holds up well to his pawing it around and even dropping it off of the sofa. However, he has tried to chew on it to get the treats out and this definitely was not meant to be a chew toy (teeth marks appeared quite quickly!). When he starts gnawing on it, I take it away from him since usually that's when there's nothing left. I think he could make quick work of destroying it if left alone.

3) The way you adjust the flow of kibble according to the box is to cut off the little prongs on the inside of the ball that hold the kibble in (it's the same with the squirrel buddy) The only problem is that once you do that, you can't put the prongs back!

4) It is pricier than some of the other toys.

Basically, it costs a little more and it doesn't seem able to stand up to chewing like a Kong. But the way that it moves and rattles has been very different and fun for the dog.  I would definitely say this is worth keeping in the house if you need to keep your pup occupied when you are doing something, but I wouldn't recommend leaving him unattended for the day with this since an aggressive chewer could probably destroy it pretty quickly. For that, I'm sticking with a frozen Kong or the squirrel dude!

Oh and one other thing--I bought all the large sizes of these toys for my dog, and they are all the same color! (I guess they use color to differentiate between sizes). That's okay but I do wish they were different colors. We have way too many purple toys in this house.

Update 6/2013:  Some of the plastic bumpers have worn off, but the toy has still held up okay!

I think if you're on a budget and/or buying food for a animal shelter or providing food for strays that might normally starve, Friskies is a good alternative (to providing nothing), but I wouldn't give this to my family member...

Original Review: What can I say other than he eats it if he gets hungry but I almost always see leftovers when I leave it out all day, so he's not particularly in love with this. A lot of vets seem to now recommend not leaving pet food out all day (because if they're indoor cats and not very active, they can get quite fat), but instead establishing feeding times (in morning when you get up, early evening when you get home and then just before you go to bed, then you put the food away after 1/2 hour out each time).

Anyway, after I run out of this, I'll end up doing what some animal specialists recommend, and that means mixing a high quality grain free canned and  bagged dry cat food (that has real meat and fish as the primary ingredients and not rice). They also suggest mashing in steamed veggies (broccoli, carrots, zucchini) and some leftover meat or fish I have for myself (chicken, steak, salmon), but we'll see how long I can keep that up.
summary: Price using S&S made it worth it, but cat isn't  crazy about it.

I fed my kitty this Friskies indoor chicken wet food before making what the manufacturer Purina describes as "the switch" to the more expensive Purina One white chicken healthy metabolism wet cat food.  I recently fed my kitty the Friskies indoor again.  She eats both the Friskies and the Purina One products with relish. I was prompted to explore the differences between the two brands. There are many sites which rate cat food, but I found few if any which put two products from the same manufacturer at different price points side by side.  The Friskies product is a pate, while Purina One is chunks in gravy.  That difference makes no particular difference to my cat, but it might to yours. Let's look at the ingredients and nutritional levels, as shown by Purina's own information.

Friskies indoor lists the first six ingredients, following water as: chicken, liver, meat-by-products, rice, corn bran, spinach.  The ingredients for Purina One, again following water are: chicken, liver, wheat gluten, meat-by-products, fish,  corn-starch modified.  The first two ingredients are identical while the Friskies in fact has a third element with nutritional value, the by-products in place of Purina One's wheat gluten. Of course this does not take account of different proportions, which are not given in the ingredient list.  In addition, Purina One has by-products as its fourth ingredient and also includes fish as an element of nutriment. There seems to be a slight advantage to Purina One in terms on nutrient content.

Now, let's look at the analysis of vitamin and mineral content, again using Purina's information.  Friskies shows the following:  protein: 7%, fat 3 %, fiber 0.95 %, moisture, 78%, taurine 0.05%.  For Purina One, the figures are: protein 11 %, fat 2%, fiber 1.5%, moisture 82%, and taurine 0.07.  In addition Purina One breaks out the nutritional content of 1-carnotine and omega 6 fatty acids, which are not shown separately for Friskies.  the Purina One product has a higher level of protein, fiber, moisture, and taurine as well as a lower level of fat.  Thus, it appears to have a substantial advantage nutritionally over the Friskies.

The above comparison suggests that Purina One is substantially more nutritious than the Friskies.  I can't asses whether the nutritional difference is sufficient to justify the price differential.  The Purina Product which comes in 2.9 oz tins is more than twice as expensive, for two cans, as one can of  the Friskies which is sold in the larger 5.5 oz can.  Both products are described as nutritionally complete for adult cats.

The preferences of your cat and your budget will likely be the determining factor in deciding between the two brands. I will continue to use the Purina One for the chicken portion of kitty's diet, but I will use the Friskies as well for occasional variety and to reduce overall cost.

Robin Friedman
summary: Friskies Indoor Chicken and Purina One White Meat Chicken Healthy Metabolism Compared

When my Mastiff was a puppy, he got one of these as a gift; when I found out what they cost, at first I thought they were overpriced.  He removed the rope part within ten minutes, and I figured he'd have the soft ball in pieces shortly thereafter, as he has and had a business-like attitude toward toys.  It rolled easily across my tile floors, however, and he tired himself out chasing it and pouncing on it, and went to sleep, leaving it in a corner.  The next morning, however, I gave it 15 minutes, as he was after it and 'caught' it every few minutes, puncturing the surface so that the ball whistled.

Fast forward to Chico as a 5-year-old; his favourite puppy toy is still his favourite, although it now resembles orange peel with the toothmarks, has myriad small holes and a couple of larger ones, and is no longer completely round. The ball has survived countless hours of hard play including being thrown and retrieved, teething, falling into the pool, being left outside in Nevada summer sun, washed with cleanser, and occasionally being sat on by a dog who weighs over 200 pounds, as well as bitten every time it is 'caught'. I bought him a new one for his birthday, and he loves it as much as the old one, but you can tell he's no puppy any longer -- he has left the rope in this one. I changed my mind -- this ball is worth every penny, with or without the rope. I actually bought two of these critters.

The first purchase was on impulse at a local grocery store. I took a little time to get around opening the box. When I did the assembly was easy. However the parts that hold the battery from releasing kept falling out. I think this was due to the store getting a pallet of leftovers. I eventually put it together and the little wand when around all the way about two times and then decided to stop forever and just wiggle back and forth a little bit. This was still enough to keep the cats occupied. I would find the cover flipped up in the little wand every once in a while missing. It would always turn up in some obscure place and I can always put it back in.

Because this critter was so cheap I decided to take a second chance. This time though I ordered it online. As cats will they help me open the box. This time I knew what to do so I did not need to read the instructions. To my surprise I found the plastic in the battery holding compartment warped. Now I know that this company can care less about quality control (Made in China.) However after forcing the batteries in and applying the math and setting it down, the critter went to work right away, wheeling this way and that, then stopping a second and anticipating that cat's next move. Soon the whole menagerie was around it. One cat would walk off and pretend he didn't care; the next minute he would be sitting on the cover. Even cats that don't get along found themselves cooperating in dispatching the mysterious wand. In the second attempt the batteries even lasted longer.

It does work well on carpets and keeps most of those little feline critters from bugging you every five minutes to play. However it had no effect on the claim to stop clawing and scratching; luckily I have one of those triangular cardboard scratch pads.

This critter uses three C cell batteries that do not come with the product. I replaced them three times in a month; so I suggest bulk purchase.

So why the good rating? Because I can now read my book in silence. I do not mind missing the lap cat that reaches up just as I am getting engrossed.

I suggest you buy two also and keep one as a backup.

====================

I recently adopted a 10 month old chocolate lab mix.  She weighs almost 60 pounds and was found as a stray so she has never had any formal training.  I started her on a regular collar and leash walk and she was not walking with me well at all.  I next moved to a harness and while she began walking better, she would jump, bark, and lunge at other dogs as we walked past.  I believe she has a bit of a leash aggression that we are working on to fix.
I finally put her on the gentle leader.  Although it was a bit difficult to fit to her head correctly by myself, I did get it to fit correctly.  She hated it the first hour it was on.  She was constantly trying to get the nose part off and would not walk at all.  Training her to walk with it correctly was a little difficult but we worked on it for an hour and half or so.  She finally began to calm down and was walking properly with me within the hour.
I took her for her first morning walk on the Gentle Leader this morning.  I live in an apartment complex with many other dogs and she has been really difficult to control when we get around the other dogs.  Today though, she was a completely different dog.  There was no pulling, no barking, no lunging, nothing.  She was even able to sit next to me as I spoke to another woman in my neighbor with a lab as well.  It is like night and day.  It truly is amazing the difference the Gentle Leader makes. I highly recommend anyone getting one.
As a quick note, the Gentle Leader is NOT a muzzle.  While it goes around their nose, it does not act as a muzzle and will not prevent biting.

I saw other reviewers mentioning that this was a little snug for their average size cats. My cat is small even though she is full grown, so I decided to give it a try.

Specific Notes:
Wire edges give it form. For the most part it holds up fine. Unfortunately it does sometimes 'squish' in a little, but never more than a few inches (not enough to even touch the cat inside).

The zippers have little clips so your cat can't try and push against where the zippers meet to open them and get out. Great idea! Sadly, one of the little tabs came off my first time using it. Looks like the sewing machine had run out of thread. Easy fix with some super glue or hot glue gun.

My cat always meowed in the old cardboard carrier. In here, she loves watching out and stays quiet. ..Unless I'm bumping her around. But that's me and not the carrier. Sorry kitty!

End result: I'm glad I bought this, and would recommend it for other owners of smaller than average cats.

WARNING:  Contains VOLCANIC ASH, recognized carcinogen, heavy-metal-laced toxic material given GRAS status in 1977 for use in FOOD CONTAINERS ONLY, not allowed for human consumption.

This is the same review I have posted for the other verified purchases of this brand's products, applying to both the dog and cat food containing Volcanic Ash, also commonly called Montmorillonite and Bentonite Clay.

I found this food brand on Dog Food Advisor, a site I love and trust, even today, and began using the Instinct Rabbit, Duck and Lamb for dogs and cats, the canned varieties, with my cat and dogs. We first used the food over a year ago, with health consequences we are still attempting to figure out. However, after a few months of dedicated, exclusive dietary use for our cat, she went into liver failure. The dogs became ill and are recovering after withdrawing the food. The cat's condition is difficult and, unfortunately, we don't know how that is going to play out but our vet is hopeful. Years ago, we had an incident with a different cat and a different food, garlic causing Heinz Anemia. We thought that was irresponsible, using garlic with dogs and cats when they are not human and cannot ingest the same chemicals. This makes that look like nothing. Montmorillonite Clay, also called Bentonite Clay and, most commonly, called Volcanic Ash, is a substance comprised of various minerals and toxic metals. The circulating folk wisdom is that this substance has an ionic charge that makes it impossible for the high levels of toxic metals and radioactive isotopes found within to leach from the ash into your system. Basic chemistry throws this out the window. What is worse, ionic charge is not the issue. Acid leaching is the issue. In the same way that acid in Orange Juice will leach lead from a leaded crystal goblet and that tomato sauce will leach lead and other metals from clay cookware and clay utensils, the human stomach, with a pH of around 3, will leach from Clay/Ash. A dog has a pH  of 1.5 to 2. A cat has a pH of 1. Again, this chemical soup is not allowed in human food, with our less acidic stomachs, because our less acidic stomachs will leach lead and aluminum and arsenic and mercury from this toxic substance. Our bodies, in response, will sweat metal, excrete metal in our waste, store metal in our fat, all in an attempt to rid ourselves of what we have ingested from a less acidic stomach leaching less of the heavy metals in this than our dogs and cats will leach.

When we went to our Veterinarian and then to our Internal Medicine Specialist, they each had us discuss all possible issues, all supplements and foods, as we are very into holistic medicine. Both honed in on the same issue almost immediately. The Instinct brand of food uses Montmorillonite Clay (Bentonite Clay, Kaolin, Ash, what have you) and this is poison, simply and plainly, an active poison. This substance was last evaluated by the FDA in 1977. As stated earlier, it was declared to be GRAS (Generally Regarded As Safe) for use in packaging (in the cardboard itself, as a drying agent and in silica packets) but was not declared safe for use in food. In other words, it is not technically legal to use this in food. In 2016, the FDA warned a company that had started selling this clay for human ingestion to stop doing so and warned consumers that it is not safe, due, primarily, to lead contamination and the high likelihood of lead poisoning. No research was done into the effects of the clay, whether or not anyone got sick, and I have been informed that none will be, as the warning was given and the consumer has access to all the information they need in the GRAS database. Basically, the FDA leaves it up to you and me to look up this chemical and be smart enough not to ingest it. And, still, here it is, in cat and dog food.

Ash or Clay is made up of Silica, Aluminum, Lead, Uranium, Mercury, Arsenic, etc. It contains radioactive isotopes, lending to the ionic charge that some people cite as the magic that will stop your body from absorbing these and other chemicals upon ingestion of this toxic substance.  There is a belief that the ionic charge of clay makes it safe, keeping the lead and aluminum from being absorbed by the body binding them. This is, forgive the expression, bunk. Ionic charge is unrelated to acid-leaching. In Mexico, during a tragic time when children were dying without explanation, it was discovered that clay cookware was poisoning them. Ionic charge did not stop leaching of metals into acidic foods and it will not stop this from leaching into your baby's body.

The worst part of the issue with this additive, not including what is happening in our family, is that we all have different tolerances and our bodies will react differently to this toxic substance. Some can ingest this for years before developing cancer or liver failure. Some, with weak livers or weak immune systems, will get sick immediately. Animals with sensitive livers will often turn up their noses at this food brand, from what I was told, because they learn the taste of metals, the substances that make them feel ill. The radioactive isotopes weaken the immune system, as does lead, as do many elements in the clay, such that cancer and immune reactivity syndromes can occur, along with unexplained illness and repeated infection. Liver failure is only one possible consequence of ingesting Volcanic Ash and it can occur months or years later, as exposure is cumulative. The way that the body purges itself of metals is complex and involves multiple organ systems, including the skin. Our bodies will even resort to storing metals in our fat cells when the metals can't be purged safely. We end up with metal deposits in the brain. In studies, Montmorillonite Clay was found to cross the blood-brain barrier and cause cell lysis (cell death) but, oddly, not in cancer cells, which don't seem to mind the substance one bit. Had our girl not had this reaction so early in our use of Instinct pet food, we could have poisoned all of our dogs right along with her, over the course of who knows how many months or years. Our vet said that "idiopathic liver failure" is often attributed to food additives years after animals have died, by owners who remember using a product that contained a substance the industry no longer uses. Most companies stopped using Ash after it was found to cause cancer and liver failure. Instinct changed the name and assumed that none of us would figure it out.

The FDA, notorious for allowing dangerous substances in food and cosmetics, does not allow Volcanic Ash, Montmorillonite Clay, Bentonite Clay, Kaolin, etc., in food, for the obvious toxic danger it poses, an issue we have known about for decades. If this substance is unsafe for human consumption, with our less efficient acid-leaching stomachs, then this substance is more unsafe for dogs and still less safe cats than even their beautiful siblings. Please understand, you shouldn't be giving this additive to any animal, ever. I rarely say, in the absolute, that you should never use a product. However, this entire pet food company should be off limits until they remove Ash/Clay from their products, remove, not rename.

I decided to try this to see if I could get her to quit this behavior, which seemed to occur *maybe* once a week or so.  Really, not that often, but often enough that I wanted to try to resolve it.

Followed the directions exactly, using the litter I use most often with them, which happens to be the Precious Cat litter (they both have allergies, so I have to use low-dust non-scented litter).  Within 24 hrs, she started pooping outside the box once or twice *a* *day*.  She was still using the box to pee, but It was almost as if she was specifically avoiding using the litter box for pooping.  Not good.  I kept trying for 10 days, and finally gave up.

Clearly, this works for some cats, judging by some of the other reviews here.  But for my cats, it not only didn't work, it made it worse.  I love the Precious Cat litter, but not this stuff.

so while I do admit the plastic is rigid cheap stuff and we had to put Teflon tape around the connection to the hose (yes , it has a rubber washer but that did not help)  I got tired of it dripping on me. I do have to say this did pick up debris at the bottom of the pond. it does not uproot plants ( as we tried to use it to pick up some weeds with no luck) but small leaves that were down there were all sucked up, a few snails (live or dead) and some of the muck.
it is a bit slow going as the bag fills and then the smallest particles come out and cloud the water. but if you stop as soon as it starts to cloud the cloud settles by the time you rinse the bag and get going again. when you get the bag filled, lift it out slowly so water can drain or you may snap the pole by the additional weight of water in the bag, the pole does sag when the bag is full.
I did not bother to try to use the brush attachment to clean the rocks as I did think that would not do anything but break the pole.
this unit does add water to your pond as you go, so clean on a day when the pond is low anyway.
I tried to attach a short length of backwash hose to the outlet instead of the bag (I wanted to just vac the water out and not deal with cleaning the bag) but the water would not go up the backwash hose.  so don't bother trying that.
all in all, this does pick up muck, it is slow going but will get the job done. I found it best to sight out a good dirty area, then put the vac right to the dirty area and not move it too much so it can pick up all the muck.
for the money, its a good way to try out a pond vac.
one last thing, even the smaller 3 inch fish stayed clear of it so I will say its safe around the fish.
UPDATE: 2015 we broke down and put in a real filter, cost a ton but now the pond is easy to keep clean running it just a few times per season. this vac took too much time for a large pond. with an installed filter, you just have to stir up the muck, and let the filter do its job. back wash and  your good to go.
