reviewText:
What makes this harness so much more unique than other harnesses is that it has both a front AND back clip. There are pros and cons to front and back clip harnesses.

Back clip pros: better control if you need it, and safer than a collar. eg, jumps in front of a car, another dog lunges at him, etc.
Back clip cons: re-enforces "sled pulling" activity (which is what you're probably trying to eliminate)

Front clip pros: causes dog to turn toward you, but does create sled pulling action. Also more agreeable (in my opinion) to the dog than a gentle leader.
Front clip cons: when the dog learns good leash behavior, he can trip over the leash since it's in front of him.

This harness is the best of both worlds! I used the front clip when I was leash training my dog to reduce the pulling reaction, but also encourage her to turn toward me when I needed it. Now that she is trained and can keep a good leash, I move the clip to the back where she won't trip on it. If she gets excited and needs some re-enforcement of her manners, I simply move the clip back to the front to remind her. My dog is also working on her leash reactivity and de-sensitizing to other dogs. When we go on training walks with other dogs, I choose to keep the leash in back. Even though it encourages pulling, I have found that if she lunges I can better control her. With the front clip on, she will trip and potentially get hurt if I have to pull her back for safety. (I should also note that she already had good leash manners and recall--ie, will look to me if I need her attention--before we started these walks with other dogs)

Most harnesses force you to choose between the front and the back. Both the front and back clip serve different purposes so I was delighted to find on that had both and can fit my dog's training needs! I highly recommend getting this harness!

reviewText:
My cat doesn't really seem to be too keen on being brushed...
Tried some other brushes laying around the house and the cat either gave me dirty looks before running away or took a swipe at the brush in a vain attempt to murder it.

When I got this one, she started warming up to the brushing a little bit. There are times I think she might even be starting to enjoy it, judging from the purring I hear. The tines (is that the right word?) are very fine, but have not snapped off or got bent up. Despite the low price it is holding up better than expected. Especially since no one has tried to murder it.

My wife's cat can't get enough of this thing and wants every inch of her body scrubbed down like in that movie Silkwood. Since she is more of what you would call a "normal" cat, if there is such a thing, I'd assume most cats will eat it up.

It's not exactly self-cleaning, since one has to make the huge effort of pressing the button on the back and scraping the hair off into the trash can. Seriously, an infant could do it! It is probably the easiest thing about owning a cat I've run into so far. (With the possible exception of when a cat eats it's vomit off the carpet. Cats are self-cleaning? Who knew!)

I'd highly recommend this item. Normal cats love it and the other cats? Well, at least they don't try to kill it.

Quit wasting your time reading my review and buy it. This thing rocks.
summary: Best cat brush I've ever seen

This is too small for a betta fish (or any fish). I know it seems counterintuitive but most pet stores and suppliers are misinformed about bettas. Learn about betta fish and their care from breeders and enthusiasts (like the Nippy Fish site), NOT sellers. To dispel some common myths about bettas:

- They do not live in small dirty puddles in the wild. The recommended tank size is 5+ gallons. They need at LEAST 1 gallon, and 2.5 gallons and up is much better.
- They shouldn't be with or near other bettas unless breeding.
- They are carnivores and need carnivore fish food. They do not eat plants, and they shouldn't eat dried pellets, flakes or freeze-dried food, which bind them up.
- They need heated water (75-80).
- They need a clean tank just like every other fish.
- A single betta with the correct supplies for living by itself will cost about $100. Or it can live in a larger aquarium with certain types of other fish.

Hope that helps!

The only human food that she gets as a treat s a sliver of apple of cucumber, salmon, a cooked egg, or a piece of cheese. This is occasional. She is a 50 pounds 5 year old Chow 25% , Boston Terrier 25% , and the rest Doggo Argento, Sharpei, Pit, Bull terrier mix. Yup her grandparents were hippies in the 60's so obviously they were very promiscuous :) She looks like a Lab/shepherd mix her DNA test picked these breeds. I rescued her 2.5 years ago.

She is a picky eater especially her wet food. Since the only meat I eat is salmon, I thought I would make that her main protein source. I did a bit research of research and found that wolves do eat salmon in Alaska; the bears catch the salmon and the wolves scavenge on what's left behind.

I wanted to feed her really premium dog food. Dog food with Salmon as the first ingredient and not just meal and fillers. I chose Blue Buffalo Basics - Salmon and potato for her dried food + Blue Buffalo Basics - Salmon wet food.  I would take 1 cup of the dried food and add 6 ounces of the wet food. I tried adding broth. I tried adding 6 ounces of human pink salmon. She would take a bite here and there , She would eat the whole thing but it would take her hours. By then there would flies and ants all over her bowl. So finally after two years I decided to try a non-salmon wet food.

I bought Paul Newsman's brand organic chicken formula which she kind of liked and then I discovered Trader Joe's Chicken Chunks that she loves. I use the same amount of 6 ounces of the wet food with her dried food. It's 1/2 of the price of other products, it has all natural ingredients, and she licks her bowl clean in 5 minutes flat. I am one happy Papa now!

Please note I don't over feed her so that she has a long healthy life. She is healthy, has a shiny coat, and is maintaining her 50 pound girlish figure. I don't want her to get hip problems when she gets older.

I purchased our Omega Paw Tricky Treat Ball (large size) almost 6 years ago, and am still using the same one. Recently I had to search my past purchases to find the exact one to recommend to a friend and thought I'd add a review.

Our bull terrier/parson terrier mix uses this for meals and as a "snack" to slow him down but also keep him active/entertained. When he's done, I pop the inner lip out, pour water in and shake and empty/let dry and it goes in with the feeding supplies. Because he can destroy other toys fast we decided early on that food-reward toys like this would be ones that had to be closely supervised.

It's a great size for him to pick up, throw and shake to get the dry dog food/kibble out of. He'll use his nose and roll it down the hall way. It's not neat and clean, I often have to sweep a bit because there's kibble debris. But he has fun. It also takes him longer, but that's why I use this particular toy more for snacks or when I want him to take a longer time to eat (when I know he's not really hungry/ it's not meal time). For meals when I want him to not spread his food across the room and down the hall, I pull out the StarMark Bob-A-Lot Interactive Dog Toy.

For larger dogs, and major chewers, this may not be the best choice. Initially when we got it, and he couldn't get it out, instead of chewing at it, he just walked away like whatever, not worth my effort.

For us, it's been a hit, and lasted quite awhile (going on 5 years now).
summary: Can be a good options, for dogs who are not boredom chewers.

reviewText:
I purchased one of these for my medium sized (45 pounds) dog to use with her harness so she wouldn't become a projectile in the event of an accident.  I have no fault to find with the adapter itself but, unfortunately, my dog is not only too smart for her own good but I'm convinced she's also the reincarnation of Houdini.  It only took three car rides for her to figure out how to apply weight on the release button of the seat belt to free herself.  Just to make sure that wasn't just a lucky accident on her part, I buckled her up again and watched as she maneuvered her rear feet onto the release button while standing up on it.  Sigh.  She also knows how to open dog gates, sliding and bi-fold doors as well as the double latched door to her kennel.  She has also figured out how to unclip her harness so, even if I do find the perfect dog-proof car restraint, she can still free herself whenever she so desires.

In conclusion, this adapter is probably wonderful for small to mid sized dogs who are content with merely looking out of  car windows and lack the motivation or the necessary problem solving skills to figure out how to release themselves.
summary: The problem is my dog, not the adapter

To get a struggling cat into this, we found it easiest to wrap him in a towel first, then put the cat burrito into the bag and zip it up; obviously this won't work if you're using the bag for bathing, but since we were just using it to avoid being clawed  while cleaning ears, it worked out just fine.

Once in there, he could thrash and claw all he wanted but all he managed to do was roll a bit like a sad burrito with a cat head.

He still peed (no worries, the bag is easy to wash), but he got his ears cleaned without the worry of him thrashing or causing bleeding of the two humans present.

We never did use the muzzle on him, as that seemed to stress him out even more than the bag and he never did try to bite when we cleaned his ears anyway so it wasn't necessary.

Overall I like the bag a lot. The condensed bricks are okay also but are honestly a pain to get out of brick form. You really need to sit there and spill water on it while chipping away the 'puffed up' bits for an hour. This stuff, which difficult to hydrate since it floats, is still a quicker and easier option.

When cleaning the cage I sit my froggy princess in a safe containment cage and proceed to overhaul her living space. I have one of those mini brush and dust pans (since it is really messy stuff) and just use it to shovel out the majority then brush the rest in to the pan. Takes about 2 minutes that way instead of playing with papertowels and such.

 Once everything is out and the glass is cleaned up I just dump about 3 inches of new bedding around her 18x18 cage then dump in some water and (with two chopsticks) mix and whisk the coconut fiber in to the water until it is hydrated. I fiddle with it a bit and add more coconut fiber and water until I have roughly 3 inches of bedding around the entire cage for her to burrow. Overall she seems to like it and, while it is messy stuff, seems easy enough to care for save for the 'easily drying out' thing I am still trying to work on.

I'm not sure whether this product has done anything or not.  I've been using it for two months this time around.  The first time I used it was when I brought home a new cat that was very aggressive -- actually that was before the multicat version came out.  Since Comfort Zone is intended to reduce anxiety I figured it wasn't a fair test.  The new cat, as it turned out, just has an aggressive personality, and my other cat wasn't really bothered by her aggression -- he's a mellow guy.
Now, over 2-1/2 years later, mellow guy started spraying and peeing in inappropriate places.  New cat had upped her aggression in certain areas and a mutual game of ambush-at-the-litter-box had begun.  I'd guess this was an indication that mellow guy was stressed, but a combination of adding additional litter boxes in other rooms and using Comfort Zone didn't solve the problem (and yes, I had a veterinarian check him out).  I got mellow guy back to the litter box by placing a box with a "cat attract" litter in the same room where he was peeing inappropriately.  I almost didn't order the refill of Comfort Zone after the first 30 days but I decided to when it seemed that the aggression between the two cats was becoming more frequent and vicious.  Now I'm nearing the end of the refill and I'm not sure if I'll refill it again.  Other reviewers seem to have had better results.  I guess I can say in my household it has just taken the edge off the situation.  Mellow guy is actually less mellow and aggressive girl is a just bit less aggressive.
summary: Product Has Helped Some -- I Think

I have three pugs all about two years old. When we first got them we installed some permeant metal gates on each side of the living room which divides the house so we can keep them either in the back of our home with access to the garden or in the kitchen. Its great but sometimes you need an extra temporary gate.

When my husband does some DIY around the house in the bedroom or in the bathroom the pups get extremely sad if they are shut out by a solid door. This gate is a very nice temporary solution for blocking a doorway while letting our doggies watch from the other side.

This particular gate is nice because it is fairly light weight and not too high. Its high enough to deter 15  20lb pugs from trying to jump over while at the same time being low enough for my husband and I to step over it fairly easily. (I am 58 and my husband is 6.)

The gate is fairly typical of this style with a diagonal plastic mesh that your pets can see through . A pair of hinged bars one with a row of notches while the top bar locks into. You slide the two halves to change the width and the row of notches let you lock it at your chosen width. It works well though I felt the wood could have been finished a bit better. It is slightly rough when you slide your hand over it, but not rough enough that you will get a splinter or a knitted garment caught on it.

The one thing to remember when you put it up is to make sure the locking bars are on the opposite side to your pets. Not because they can open it, but we caught them gnawing on those locking bars because they are the only thing within easy reach and easy to sink teeth into.

When installed in the doorway the pressure on the rubber stops on each side do hold firm without leaving marks on the door frame. When its not blocking a doorway we  lean it extended across a small bookshelf to protect the lower row of books having their spines chewed.

All in all we like the gate and it is reasonably priced.  I recommend it.
summary: Good gate but be careful to put the locking mechanism where little teeth can't get to it

reviewText:
What caught my attention to this shampoo was where one of the reviewers said that she could get by with using less of it when bathing her Yellow Lab. I was hesitant to buy it because of the price. I thought that it may just be cheap shampoo in a fancy bottle. It turns out I was wrong and she was exactly right. You really can use less soap.

My dachshund has sensitive skin along with an allergy to fleas.  We use a Frontline type flea treatment but she still gets the occasional flea bite. The hot dry weather here was wonderful for producing a bumper crop of fleas. It also caused my poor little dog's skin to be extra dry. She was constantly scratching, even losing sleep because she'd wake up and have to scratch.

We used the Tropiclean shampoo today. We followed the instructions to the letter making sure we left the soap on for 5 to 10 minutes. Our Doxie does not like being wet so like always she fought us and tried to escape. Then a funny thing happened. She quit fighting and raised her head up in her "Oh this feels so good." manner. She stood and let us wash her with no problem. Like the reviewer with the Yellow Lab said we used less soap than with other brands. My former brand was the Petco generic brand soap. As soon as i got it on my hands I could even feel the difference in quality. This soap had a thicker, richer, finer feel to it. It also had a good smell.

The Tropiclean had an immediate effect on my dog. It was three hours ago that I washed her and she has not scratched yet. In fact after we were done she had a lot of energy. Watching her frolic was well worth the money I paid for this shampoo. One last thing... Before the bath I could scratch her back and she would raise her back paw involuntarily and scratch like dogs do when you scratch just right. After the bath she quit doing that. Try as I might I could not get her to do that.  That proved to me the shampoo did it's job very well.

We have used oatmeal based shampoo before but the Tropiclean has a form of tea in it and apparently that boosts the effect of the oatmeal. Whatever is in it it is absolutely the best dog shampoo I have ever used. Just be sure and follow those instructions. I also found out that the company that sells this stuff is located not very far from where I live. The next time I am in that town I'll be stocking up.
summary: I'd Give This Ten Stars if I Could!!!

I read several complaints about cloudy water, but I haven't had any problems.

I rinsed everything very well before I filled the aquarium.  I added 4 small live plants, a pagoda for the fishy to hide in, gravel, and a heater.  I filled it with spring water, and added one Betta fish.

A week later, the plants and fish are healthy.  The water is clear.  There is an evaporation issue, I keep a gallon of spring water on stand-by and top off the tank every other day (about 1 cup).  The aquarium manager at my local fish store said in my set up with only one Betta, I'll only need to do a 20% water change about every 2 weeks.  She also has a chi with a few live plants and Betta and said she has never had cloudy water issues.

I have a big cat that can chomp through a power cord in one bite. He's done it more times than I can count and I've spent a lot of money on new power cords. The CritterCord is my preferred solution, it can be removed when I take my power cord with me, it's clear, and the cat hasn't attempted to even nibble on it. It smells terrible and it's rather expensive considering it's just plastic tubing, but the smell is fading and I'd rather deal with the smell than buy a new power cord.

UPDATE: It's been over a year and my CritterCords and cables are still in tact. My cat still tries to nibble on the CritterCord on occasion, but he's breaking the habit. I've added a couple photos to show the CritterCord and protected power cable. The slit in the plastic tubing allows some bites to get through to the power cord, but the power cord still works.
summary: Apple's stock may go down now that I've stopped buying new power cords...

He's very squirmy, so it's hard to put on him but no star reductions for this, because as it turns out hard to put on also equals hard to take off!  He's destroyed 2 coats with velcro recently as it's very easy for him to grab the connecting pieces and yank them off.  Destruction is fun until you spend the next 5 hours cold while your puppy parents are at work!  This coat resolves one problem, huzzah!

Now the reason I'm reducing two stars is because I consider the neck on this to be a design flaw.  It's got this loose, popped collar look to it.  Unfortunately, that means he can stick his head down, grab the neck with his mouth, and chew on the coat (it also means if he's drank a bunch of water and has a drippy face, some dribbles into the coat).

We try to keep it folded down, and out of chomping/dripping range, but over the course of the day it pops up, so the neck is mangled but the rest of the coat remains in good condition.

The coat also is dangerously close to his junk and gaps slightly. I worry one of these days he's going to get pee into his coat.  Would be nice for the fabric to taper up more on that part of the coat to accommodate for male dogs (or sell separate styles for male and female dogs).  We actually could have been using this coat on him a few weeks ago if not for that part, as when it arrived it actually completely covered his junk.

Thankfully he's growing fast and it seems like we may *fingers crossed* by in the clear with regards to that issue.  It's clear that this product is not long for this world due to his chewing, but I am thankful for it's zipper back style despite it taking two people to put it on.  I wouldn't use the rings on the back for a leash, the fabric doesn't feel tough enough for a hard pulling dog.

Please note- sizing is tough.  A 6 month old Doberman puppy (granted, he's large for his age) is wearing a 6L!

He's just past 50lbs, but it's necessary for that barrel chest.

*UPDATE* no alterations to stars because it's not a product issue necessarily but may be helpful for other people with difficult dogs in need of coats- but the puppy figured out how to get it off and chew it up.  If you have a difficult dog like I do, this may give you a little more time before they destroy it, but won't ultimately save the day.  After he chewed the first one up, we got a second one, sprayed it with bitter spray where he chewed off the previous one- that bought us a couple days, but he did ultimately find a new way to chew it off.  I guess we should have doused the whole thing with bitter spray...

I have two dogs - a Boxer mix and a Rottweiler/Lab mix. Originally they were on a cheaper Iams food and - at 60-70 pounds each - were eating as much as 4 cups a day (each dog) to maintain weight. We went through two 20-pound bags of Iams each month.

Both dogs showed skin issues. My Boxer would develop red, bald patches and would chew the fur off of his rump and legs. My Rott, who is much older, had a yeast infection (or similar) on his hind end that never really went away no matter what I tried. I read about corn allergies in dogs and decided to switch them to a higher end food in an attempt to help the skin issues.

Another review mentioned the high fat content of some of the lines of TOTW. Fat is vital to skin and hair health so I believe the higher amount of fat helped heal my dogs, however it's good to rotate the flavors used to get the benefits of each one.

Benefits I experienced from TOTW:
- Eliminated allergy dermatitis in one dog, and immune system? in the other, to eliminate skin issues
- Promoted skin and coat health
- Markedly improved arthritis (Springtime, Inc. supplements, purchased later, improved even more)
- Easier to maintain weight (one dog tends to gain weight quickly... no they are not fed table scraps)
- More cost efficient and the dogs eat less. (Originally, 40 pounds and $48/month for Iams, vs. 30 pounds and $42/month for TOTW [I purchase locally])

Cons:
- More expensive up front than cheaper brands
- Still not as good as Orijen

reviewText:
I bought this at my local Petsmart and started feeding it to my 13 year old doxie.
She is a super picky eater and we end up rotating brands every few months when she gets bored. We feed Orijen, Wellness, and Performatrin. All grain free, high protein foods. Our Petsmart had a $5 off coupon and the reviews of the large breed version were wonderful so I decided to give it a try. She loves the taste of Ulitimate Protein and will take it happily as a treat. The kibble is quite small which makes it easier for her to eat. I love the quality ingredients and production process. However, since starting this food she is drinking excessively,  in turn urinating 7-8 times a day, panting a lot and always seems hungry. She's vocally begging when anyone is eating anything. Her bowel movements are great though small and as odorless as poop can be, this food is highly digestible. I think it just has too much sodium for her little old lady body to handle. She's had more accidents in the last few days then she's had since we adopted her a year ago. I'm switching her to the Nature's Variety Grain Free dry kibble. It has less protein and less sodium, we'll see how it goes. I would recommend this food for younger small breed dogs that are more active.
summary: Doxie loves this food, it doesn't love her back.

Well, this light looked great. While it worked. That's about where the positives stop.

First off, this thing is poorly designed. The power supply housing actually has holes in it where you can see the circuit board. Not sure why they would do that, as this should be a completely sealed waterproof unit, as are all of my other aquarium power supplies, but perhaps they felt it would be easier to build a housing the breathes rather than one that is sealed? Also, the feet that hold the light on to the tank do not lock on to the top of a glass aquarium, so it's likely to fall in when you take the top off of your tank for cleaning. I used double sided tape to stick the feet to my tank.

Those I could have lived with, except for 2 things - it generated so much radio frequency interference as to make my licensed radio station unusable when the light is on. But the worst part is that it worked for about an hour and then stopped. I turned it off and unplugged it to see if I could suppress the RF noise with a ferrite choke, and when I plugged it back in, it wouldn't turn on!

Needless to say, this is going back to Amazon.

Update: I obtained a replacement, and somehow got it in the non-functional state again. I'm not sure exactly what fixed it, but some combination of mashing buttons got it working again. The second unit also generates a heck of a lot of RF noise.

Update 2/2/16: I have been in contact with the manufacturer about the RF noise. They seem responsive, and concerned about the problem. I isolated the problem to the power supply, and found that their manufacturer intentionally left out an inductor that should have filtered the RF noise. I've added a star for the customer service received, and will update further if the issue is corrected.

Update 3/7/16: The manufacturer sent me a new power supply with the inductor installed which has quieted the noise. That puts this light into the range of tolerable and even decent. With a few design improvements it could be a great light.

He is a puppy, so he does, on occasion, try to move in an inconvenient (to me) direction.  The short leash does not permit much wandering.  Having seen him immobilize others by wrapping them about the legs with his usual leash, I feel that I definitely hold the advantage in this situation. He is a sweet dog who aims to please, but I think the short leash reinforces what is expected of him.  Of course, this walking beside me is not his only opportunity for exercise.  That would be cruel.  He has a large, fenced in area for chasing after balls, rolling on the grass, etc.  He is also being trained to a standard leash and a very, very long training leash.  They all have their specific purposes.  He also responds to a whistle.
summary: A short leash, properly used, can be quite helpful in some situations

I honestly think this works.

First of all, our doggie girl doesn't like it, and rolls around the floor after we put it on her. But that only lasts a couple of minutes.

Best to apply under the top coat if you can as close to skin as possible but the top will be okay....you'll just have to do more frequent applications.

Directions say reapply when the smell (which I love) goes away, but it seems to last longer than that. Our girl goes to dog parks and to doggie day care, plays hard, gets into all sorts of things in the yard, etc., and we've yet to see a flea on her.\

After applying as directed, we also use a few drops of essential lavendar oil under and around her collar, at the base of her spine, and on the top of her head.

She's happy and healthy! And we are so happy we don't have to use harsh chemicals.

We have never been much of a brushing household as the cats were all domestic short hair. Now there is an addition of a young fellow who is not a long hair but has fur long enough to get mats.
His brushing has been a bit of a process as he was a bottle baby and very ill for a good while. During this his little bum was very sore and needed wiping, combing and clipping which was very uncomfortable. He really HATED brushing due to this so I was not sure he would allow this to be used. I figured to give it a go as the only other solution would be a lion cut.
The brush is very well made, I see some do complain about the bristles, These are to get to the deep guard hairs on a longer furred cat so they really do need to be fine.  Very solid and has a nice heft and is easy to hold.
Now an odd thing I noticed with my furmaly. They all really needed to sniff it up. I mean to an unusual extent. Each cat I brushed insisted on grabbing the brush and putting the bitey on it for some time before they would allow brushing. They have never done this with any other brush or comb and it may be the plastic this is made of. I would really like to hear if your cat does this.

OK the brushing
Once each cat bit the brush enough to put it in its place they relaxed and really enjoyed the brushing. I am now a confirmed cat brushing guy as this makes it so easy. Brush brush brush brush... Then push the button and out comes the fur. Repeat. Very easy Very nice.
Even the little fellow is getting into the act.
Thanks Safari!

reviewText: Quality Product.

I received a case of (6) two-packs for a total of 12 cartridges.  I liked the item of ordering in bulk.  Since a case arrived, there was no unused space and I left the cartridges in the same box for storage.  I didn't feel wasteful like do with other shipments when they arrive in oversized boxes with packing materials that I need to break down and recycle.  The cartridges are exactly the ones that fit my Litter Genie Plus.  I have two (one for each litter box) and two cats.  I figure I am all set for about a year or so.  Each cartridge is supposed to last up to two months with one cat. I empty my indoor genie once a week on trash pickup day.  The second one in the garage for the lessor used litter box goes out as needed.  I am in Califorina where we have a bag ban so I can't get free grocery bags anymore and would have to buy bags anyway.  The Litter Genie just makes the process so much easier.
summary: I am in love with my Litter Genies!

I've now had this litter box for about a month. Though it's smaller than the box we had before, this one is great simply because of the ease of use.

We recently added a washing machine in the room that used to house the litter box and a spare fridge. The washing machine took up the space of the old box. This one sit comfortably on top of the washer, and the cats have no problem getting in and out. Even in the relatively cramped space, I can still turn the box easily.

On occasion, some litter will get into the seam between the top and bottom, and when this happens, the grate will disconnect, causing the whole system to mess up. However, this is a relatively quick fix, and compared to the mess of scooping you deal with with a regular litter box, I'm happy to do that once a month. Overall, it's a great idea and a great design. Four stars only for the slight inconvenience of the occasional grate issue.
summary: So much better than the average litter box
